This is a MAML-style bi-level optimization. Let θ be the meta-parameters. For each task τᵢ with loss ℒᵢ, the inner loop computes adapted parameters φᵢ = θ − α∇_θ ℒᵢ(θ) (one or more gradient steps). The outer (meta) loop then minimizes the meta-objective: min_θ Σᵢ ℒᵢ(φᵢ) = Σᵢ ℒᵢ(θ − α∇_θ ℒᵢ(θ)), updated via θ ← θ − β∇_θ Σᵢ ℒᵢ(φᵢ). The meta-gradient ∇_θ ℒᵢ(φᵢ) requires differentiating through the inner update, producing second-order terms (Hessian-vector products); first-order MAML (FOMAML) drops these for efficiency. The inner step α is the task learning rate; β is the meta learning rate. φᵢ lives in the inner loop and is discarded after each meta-update; only θ persists. This structure is equivalent to learning an initialization θ such that one gradient step generalizes rapidly to new tasks.